export const reactCourse = {
  id: 'react', title: 'React', description: 'Declarative JavaScript library for building user interfaces.',
  officialDocs: 'https://react.dev/', tutorialLink: 'https://react.dev/learn', exerciseLink: 'https://www.w3schools.com/react/react_exercises.asp',
  sections: [
    { title: 'What is React', image: '/images/react/react-virtual-dom.svg', content: `**React** is a declarative, component-based JavaScript library for building user interfaces. Created by **Facebook** (Meta) in 2013, it revolutionized frontend development with its **Virtual DOM**, one-way data flow, and component-based architecture.\n\nReact is "declarative" — you describe *what* the UI should look like for a given state, and React efficiently updates the actual DOM. This is fundamentally different from "imperative" DOM manipulation where you manually tell the browser *what to change*.\n\n### Not a Full Framework\n\nReact handles only the **View layer**. For routing, state management, and data fetching, you combine React with libraries (\`react-router-dom\`, \`Redux\`/\`Zustand\`, \`TanStack Query\`) or use full frameworks built on React (**Next.js**, **Remix**).`, keyPoints: ['Declarative UI — describe what, React handles how.', 'Component-based architecture for reusability.', 'Virtual DOM for efficient updates.', 'Not a full framework — handles only the View layer.'] },
    
    { title: 'Installation & Create App', content: `Modern React projects use **Vite** as the build tool. *Create React App* (CRA) is deprecated. Vite provides fast startup, **hot module replacement** (HMR), and optimized builds.\n\n### Full-Stack Frameworks\n\nFor full-stack applications, consider **Next.js** (server-side rendering, API routes, file-based routing) or **Remix** (full-stack web framework with nested routes). These frameworks handle routing, data loading, and deployment out of the box.\n\n### Project Setup\n\n\`\`\`bash\n# Create with Vite (recommended)\nnpm create vite@latest my-app -- --template react\ncd my-app\nnpm install\nnpm run dev\n\`\`\`\n\n\`\`\`bash\n# Create with Next.js (full-stack)\nnpx create-next-app@latest my-app\n\`\`\`\n\n### Project structure\n\`\`\`text\nmy-app/\n├── public/              # Static assets\n├── src/\n│   ├── components/      # Reusable UI components\n│   ├── pages/           # Page components\n│   ├── App.jsx          # Root component\n│   ├── main.jsx         # Entry point\n│   └── index.css        # Global styles\n├── index.html\n├── package.json\n└── vite.config.js\n\`\`\``, keyPoints: ['Use Vite for new React projects (CRA is deprecated).', 'Next.js for full-stack applications with SSR.', 'Organize: components/, pages/, hooks/, data/.', 'npm run dev starts the development server.'] },

    { title: 'Render HTML', content: `React's goal is in many ways to render HTML in a web page.\n\nReact renders HTML to the web page by using a function called \`createRoot()\` and its method \`render()\$.\n\n### The createRoot Function\nThe \`createRoot()\` function takes one argument, an HTML element. The purpose of the function is to define the HTML element where a React component should be displayed.\n\n### The render Method\nThe \`render()\` method is then called to define the React component that should be rendered.\n\n### Example: Display a paragraph inside an element\n\n\`\`\`jsx\nimport React from 'react';\nimport { createRoot } from 'react-dom/client';\n\nconst container = document.getElementById('root');\nconst root = createRoot(container);\nroot.render(<p>Hello, React!</p>);\n\`\`\`\n\n### The Root Node\nThe HTML element provided to \`createRoot()\` acts as a container for your app.\nIt is usually a \`<div>\` element with the id \`root\`, and it exists inside the \`index.html\` file:\n\n\`\`\`html\n<body>\n  <div id="root"></div>\n</body>\n\`\`\``, keyPoints: ['createRoot() is used in modern React (v18+).', 'Render targets an element in index.html (usually id="root").', 'You can render raw JSX or full React components.'] },

    { title: 'JSX Programming', content: `**JSX** stands for JavaScript XML. It allows us to write HTML directly within JavaScript, making it easier to write and add HTML in React.\n\n### Rules of JSX\n\n1. **Single Top Level Element:** JSX must return a single parent element. You can use a Fragment (\`<></>\`) if you don't want to add an extra node.\n2. **Close all tags:** Every tag must be explicitly closed, e.g., \`<br />\`, \`<input />\`.\n3. **camelCase Property Names:** HTML attributes like \`class\` become \`className\`, and \`onclick\` becomes \`onClick\`.\n4. **Expressions in JSX:** You can embed any JavaScript expression in JSX by wrapping it in curly braces \`{}\`.\n\n### Example: Variables & Expressions\n\n\`\`\`jsx\nconst name = "React Developer";\nconst sum = 2 + 2;\n\nconst element = (\n  <>\n    <h1 className="greeting">Hello, {name}!</h1>\n    <p>JSX evaluates expressions: 2 + 2 = {sum}</p>\n    <input type="text" placeholder="Closed tag" />\n  </>\n);\n\`\`\``, keyPoints: ['JSX must return a single parent element.', 'HTML attributes use camelCase (e.g., className).', 'Embed JS expressions using curly braces {}.'] },

    { title: 'Components: Class vs Functional', content: `Components are independent and reusable bits of code. They are the building blocks of any React application.\n\n### Functional Components\nThe modern and recommended way to write components. They are simpler, use Hooks for state and lifecycle, and have less boilerplate.\n\n\`\`\`jsx\n// Functional Component (Modern)\nfunction FunctionalGreeting({ name }) {\n  return <h1>Hello, {name}</h1>;\n}\n\`\`\`\n\n### Class Components\nBefore React 16.8, class components were required to hold state or use lifecycle methods. They extend \`React.Component\` and require a \`render()\` method. Though largely replaced by functional components, you will still see them in legacy codebases.\n\n\`\`\`jsx\n// Class Component (Legacy)\nimport React, { Component } from 'react';\n\nclass ClassGreeting extends Component {\n  constructor(props) {\n    super(props);\n    this.state = { count: 0 };\n  }\n\n  render() {\n    return <h1>Hello, {this.props.name}</h1>;\n  }\n}\n\`\`\``, keyPoints: ['Functional components are the modern standard.', 'Class components use this.state and this.props.', 'Class components require a render() method.'] },

    { title: 'Props & State', content: `**Props** (properties) are read-only data passed from parent to child components. They flow **one way — downward**. A parent decides what data a child receives, and the child *cannot* modify its own props.\n\n**State** is mutable data owned by the component itself. When state changes, the component **re-renders** with the new data.\n\n\`\`\`jsx\nimport { useState } from 'react';\n\nfunction Counter() {\n  // State manages internal component values\n  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);\n\n  return (\n    <div>\n      <p>Count: {count}</p>\n      <button onClick={() => setCount(prev => prev + 1)}>+1</button>\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n\`\`\`\n\n### Lifting State Up\nThe key rule: **"Lift state up."** When two sibling components need to share data, move the state to their common parent and pass it down as props.\n\n\`\`\`jsx\n// Lifting state up to a common parent\nfunction App() {\n  const [selectedId, setSelectedId] = useState(null);\n\n  return (\n    <div>\n      <Sidebar\n        selectedId={selectedId}\n        onSelect={(id) => setSelectedId(id)}  // Passed as a Prop\n      />\n      <MainContent itemId={selectedId} />       \n    </div>\n  );\n}\n\`\`\``, keyPoints: ['Props flow down (parent → child), read-only.', 'State is owned by the component, triggers re-renders.', '"Lift state up" to share data between siblings.'] },

    { title: 'Events', content: `React events are named using **camelCase**, rather than lowercase. With JSX you pass a function as the event handler, rather than a string.\n\n### Event Handlers\nYou can trigger logic on \`onClick\`, \`onChange\`, \`onSubmit\`, and more. When passing arguments to event handlers, ensure you use an arrow function to prevent the function from firing immediately when the component renders.\n\n\`\`\`jsx\nfunction ActionButton() {\n  // Event handler function\n  const handleClick = (message) => {\n    alert(message);\n  };\n\n  return (\n    <>\n      {/* DO: Pass function reference using Arrow function */}\n      <button onClick={() => handleClick("Action triggered!")}>\n        Click Me\n      </button>\n      \n      {/* DON'T: Call function directly (runs on render) */}\n      {/* <button onClick={handleClick("Wrong!")}> */}\n    </>\n  );\n}\n\`\`\``, keyPoints: ['Events use camelCase (onClick, onChange).', 'Pass a function reference, not an executed function string.', 'Use arrow functions to pass arguments to handlers.'] },

    { title: 'Conditions', content: `In React, you can conditionally render components or elements using standard JavaScript conditionals.\n\n### 1. The && Operator (Logical AND)\nUsed for rendering an element only if a condition is true.\n\n### 2. Ternary Operator\nUsed for conditionally rendering one of two elements based on a boolean.\n\n### 3. if/else Statements\nTypically used outside the \`return\` block to return entirely different JSX based on a condition.\n\n\`\`\`jsx\nfunction ConditionalRendering({ isLoggedIn, hasNotifications }) {\n  // 3. if/else Statement (Early return)\n  if (hasNotifications === undefined) {\n    return <div>Loading data...</div>;\n  }\n\n  return (\n    <div>\n      {/* 2. Ternary Operator */}\n      {isLoggedIn ? <h1>Welcome Back!</h1> : <h1>Please Log In</h1>}\n      \n      {/* 1. Logical AND */}\n      {hasNotifications && <p>You have unread messages.</p>}\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n\`\`\``, keyPoints: ['Use ternary (?) for binary conditionals in JSX.', 'Use logical AND (&&) to render if true.', 'Use if/else to return completely different functional blocks.'] },

    { title: 'Lists', content: `To render multiple items in React, you map over an array of data and return an element for each item.\n\n### The importance of keys\nEvery element rendered in a list must have a unique **\`key\`** prop. React uses these keys to track which items have changed, been added, or been removed. \n\n*Never use the array index as a key* if the list order might change, as it can cause rendering bugs and performance issues.\n\n\`\`\`jsx\nfunction UserList() {\n  const users = [\n    { id: 1, name: "Alice" },\n    { id: 2, name: "Bob" },\n    { id: 3, name: "Charlie" }\n  ];\n\n  return (\n    <ul>\n      {users.map((user) => (\n        <li key={user.id}>\n          {user.name}\n        </li>\n      ))}\n    </ul>\n  );\n}\n\`\`\``, keyPoints: ['Use the .map() array method to render lists.', 'Always provide a unique, stable "key" prop to list elements.', 'Keys help React optimize rendering performance.'] },

    { title: 'Forms, Controls & Submit', content: `In React, form data is typically managed by the component's state. This is called a **Controlled Component**.\n\n### Controlled Components\nThe input's \`value\` is tied to a \`useState\` variable, and an \`onChange\` handler updates that state as the user types.\n\n### Handling Form Submission\nUse the \`onSubmit\` event on the \`<form>\` element. Always call \`e.preventDefault()\` within your handler to prevent the default browser page reload.\n\n\`\`\`jsx\nimport { useState } from 'react';\n\nfunction ContactForm() {\n  const [name, setName] = useState("");\n  const [email, setEmail] = useState("");\n\n  const handleSubmit = (event) => {\n    event.preventDefault(); // Prevent page reload\n    alert(\`Submitted: \${name} / \${email}\`);\n  }\n\n  return (\n    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>\n      <label>\n        Name:\n        <input \n          type="text" \n          value={name} // Control value\n          onChange={(e) => setName(e.target.value)} \n        />\n      </label>\n      <label>\n        Email:\n        <input \n          type="email" \n          value={email} \n          onChange={(e) => setEmail(e.target.value)} \n        />\n      </label>\n      <button type="submit">Send</button>\n    </form>\n  );\n}\n\`\`\``, keyPoints: ['Control form inputs using React state (value & onChange).', 'Use onSubmit on the <form> element to catch submission regardless of input method.', 'Always use event.preventDefault() to stop page reloads.'] },

    { title: 'CSS & Sass', content: `React offers multiple ways to apply styles:\n\n### 1. Inline Styling\nPass a Javascript object to the \`style\` attribute. Properties use camelCase (e.g., \`backgroundColor\`).\n\n### 2. CSS Stylesheets\nImport standard \`.css\` files directly into components. These styles operate globally.\n\n### 3. CSS Modules\nFiles named \`*.module.css\`. These generate locally scoped class names to prevent style collisions.\n\n### 4. Sass\nReact supports Sass out-of-the-box (with Vite or CRA). Simply compile your \`.scss\` files and import them like standard CSS.\n\n\`\`\`jsx\nimport './global.css'; // Global CSS\nimport styles from './Button.module.css'; // CSS Module\nimport './Theme.scss'; // Sass\n\nfunction StyledComponent() {\n  // Inline CSS object\n  const inlineStyle = {\n    color: "white",\n    backgroundColor: "DodgerBlue",\n    padding: "10px"\n  };\n\n  return (\n    <>\n      <h1 style={inlineStyle}>Inline Styled</h1>\n      <p className="global-text">Global CSS Styled</p>\n      <button className={styles.primaryButton}>\n        Module Styled\n      </button>\n    </>\n  );\n}\n\`\`\``, keyPoints: ['Inline styles require camelCase property names in an object.', 'CSS modules scope styles locally to avoid clashes.', 'Sass (.scss) can be used for advanced CSS features.'] },

    { title: 'Transitions & Animations', content: `Since React immediately applies DOM changes, creating smooth UI transitions requires specific techniques or libraries.\n\n### CSS Transitions\nThe simplest way is conditionally applying a CSS class that contains a \`transition\` property.\n\n### Animation Libraries\nFor components entering and leaving the DOM, libraries like **Framer Motion** or \`react-transition-group\` provide precise control over mounting/unmounting animations.\n\n\`\`\`jsx\nimport { useState } from 'react';\nimport { motion } from 'framer-motion';\n\nfunction ToggleBox() {\n  const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = useState(false);\n\n  return (\n    <>\n      <button onClick={() => setIsOpen(!isOpen)}>Toggle</button>\n      \n      {/* 1. CSS Transition approach */}\n      <div \n        className={\`transition-box \${isOpen ? 'open' : 'closed'}\`}\n        style={{ \n          height: isOpen ? '100px' : '0px', \n          transition: 'height 0.3s ease', \n          overflow: 'hidden'\n        }}\n      >\n        Content inside the box.\n      </div>\n      \n      {/* 2. Framer Motion approach for mounting/unmounting */}\n      {isOpen && (\n         <motion.div\n           initial={{ opacity: 0, y: -20 }}\n           animate={{ opacity: 1, y: 0 }}\n           exit={{ opacity: 0, y: 20 }}\n         >\n           Animated appearing block here.\n         </motion.div>\n      )}\n    </>\n  );\n}\n\`\`\``, keyPoints: ['CSS transitions handle basic state changes smoothly.', 'Unmounting components instantly removes them from the DOM.', 'Use Framer Motion for complex spring/mount animations.'] },

    { title: 'HOC & forwardRef', content: `### Higher-Order Components (HOC)\nAn HOC is an advanced pattern where a function takes a component and returns a new component, adding extra functionality (e.g., \`withAuth\`, \`withRouter\`). While Hooks have largely replaced HOCs, they are still prevalent.\n\n### forwardRef\nBy default, you cannot pass a \`ref\` to a functional component. \`React.forwardRef\` allows a component to forward its ref to a child DOM element, enabling parent components to interact directly with that element (e.g., focusing an input).\n\n\`\`\`jsx\nimport { forwardRef, useRef } from 'react';\n\n// forwardRef Component allows Parent to link a ref down to this <input>\nconst CustomInput = forwardRef((props, ref) => {\n  return <input ref={ref} className="fancy-input" {...props} />;\n});\n\nfunction Parent() {\n  const inputRef = useRef(null);\n\n  const focusInput = () => {\n    inputRef.current.focus(); // Directly accesses the DOM node\n  };\n\n  return (\n    <div>\n      <CustomInput ref={inputRef} placeholder="Type here..." />\n      <button onClick={focusInput}>Focus Input</button>\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n\`\`\``, keyPoints: ['HOCs wrap components to provide additional capabilities.', 'forwardRef allows passing refs down to functional components.', 'Crucial for reusable UI components requiring DOM access.'] },

    { title: 'Hooks: State & Effects', content: `Hooks let functional components manage state and side effects.\n\n### useState\nDeclares a state variable and an updater function. \`const [state, setState] = useState(initialValue)\`.\n\n### useEffect\nHandles side effects (API calls, subscriptions, DOM manipulation). \n- No array: runs on every render.\n- \`[]\`: runs once on mount.\n- \`[deps]\`: runs when dependencies change.\n\n### useContext\nConsumes the nearest Context provider, avoiding "prop drilling" where data is passed through many layers manually.\n\n\`\`\`jsx\nimport { useState, useEffect, useContext, createContext } from 'react';\n\nconst ThemeContext = createContext('light');\n\nfunction BasicHooksExample() {\n  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);\n  const theme = useContext(ThemeContext);\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    document.title = \`You clicked \${count} times\`;\n    \n    // Cleanup function (runs on unmount or before re-running)\n    return () => {\n      console.log('Cleanup logic here');\n    };\n  }, [count]); // Runs when count changes\n\n  return (\n    <div className={theme}>\n      <p>Count: {count}</p>\n      <button onClick={() => setCount(c => c + 1)}>Increment</button>\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n\`\`\``, keyPoints: ['useState manages local component state.', 'useEffect handles side-effects and cleanup.', 'useContext simplifies consuming global data.'] },

    { title: 'Hooks: Advanced Tools', content: `React provides several advanced hooks for optimization and complex boundaries.\n\n### useRef\nStores a mutable value that does *not* cause a re-render when updated. Commonly used to access DOM elements directly or store timeout IDs.\n\n### useReducer\nAn alternative to \`useState\` for complex state logic involving multiple sub-values. It works conceptually like Redux reducers.\n\n### useMemo & useCallback\nPerformance optimization hooks.\n- \`useMemo\` caches the result of an expensive calculation.\n- \`useCallback\` caches a function definition to prevent unnecessary re-renders of child components that depend on it.\n\n\`\`\`jsx\nimport { useRef, useReducer, useMemo, useCallback } from 'react';\n\nfunction AdvancedHooks() {\n  const inputRef = useRef(null);\n  \n  const [count, dispatch] = useReducer((state, action) => {\n    if (action.type === 'inc') return state + 1;\n    return state;\n  }, 0);\n\n  // Caches function to prevent recreations on parent re-renders\n  const handleLog = useCallback(() => {\n    console.log(\`Count is \${count}\`);\n  }, [count]);\n\n  // Caches expensive calculation\n  const squared = useMemo(() => {\n    return count * count;\n  }, [count]);\n\n  return (\n    <div>\n      <input ref={inputRef} />\n      <button onClick={() => inputRef.current.focus()}>\n        Focus Input (using useRef)\n      </button>\n      <hr />\n      <p>Count: {count} | Squared: {squared}</p>\n      <button onClick={() => dispatch({ type: 'inc' })}>Increment (useReducer)</button>\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n\`\`\``, keyPoints: ['useRef stores values without triggering re-renders.', 'useReducer is ideal for complex state transitions.', 'useMemo/useCallback optimize rendering performance.'] },

    { title: 'Custom Hooks', content: `Custom Hooks let you extract component logic into reusable functions. A custom Hook is a JavaScript function whose name starts with \`use\` and that may call other Hooks.\n\n### Why use Custom Hooks?\nThey allow you to reuse stateful logic without changing your component hierarchy (unlike HOCs or render props). They keep your components clean by abstracting away data fetching, window sizing, or local storage syncing.\n\n\`\`\`jsx\nimport { useState, useEffect } from 'react';\n\n// 1. Custom Hook definition\nfunction useFetch(url) {\n  const [data, setData] = useState(null);\n  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    fetch(url)\n      .then(res => res.json())\n      .then(data => {\n        setData(data);\n        setLoading(false);\n      });\n  }, [url]);\n\n  return { data, loading };\n}\n\n// 2. Using the custom hook in a component\nfunction App() {\n  const { data, loading } = useFetch('/api/users');\n\n  if (loading) return <p>Loading...</p>;\n  return <ul>{data.map(u => <li key={u.id}>{u.name}</li>)}</ul>;\n}\n\`\`\``, keyPoints: ['Custom hooks must start with "use".', 'They extract stateful logic to make code reusable.', 'They can call other built-in React hooks.'] },

    { title: 'React Router & Navigation', content: `**React Router** (\`react-router-dom\`) is the standard library for client-side routing in React SPAs. It maps URL paths to components, enabling **navigation without full page reloads**.\n\n### Route Configuration\n\n\`BrowserRouter\` wraps the app and enables HTML5 history-based routing. \`Routes\` defines the route configuration — each \`Route\` maps a path to a component. **Nested routes** create layouts with shared UI (header/footer) and outlet areas for child content.\n\n### Navigation Components\n\n\`NavLink\` and \`Link\` create navigation links. \`NavLink\` automatically applies an **"active" class** when the current URL matches, making it ideal for navigation menus. \`useParams()\` extracts URL parameters, and \`useNavigate()\` enables programmatic navigation.\n\n\`\`\`jsx\nimport { BrowserRouter, Routes, Route, NavLink, useParams, useNavigate } from 'react-router-dom';\n\nfunction App() {\n  return (\n    <BrowserRouter>\n      <nav>\n        <NavLink to="/" className={({isActive}) =>\n          isActive ? 'active' : ''\n        }>Home</NavLink>\n        <NavLink to="/courses">Courses</NavLink>\n      </nav>\n\n      <Routes>\n        <Route path="/" element={<Home />} />\n        <Route path="/courses" element={<Courses />} />\n        <Route path="/courses/:id" element={<CourseDetail />} />\n        <Route path="*" element={<NotFound />} />\n      </Routes>\n    </BrowserRouter>\n  );\n}\n\n// Dynamic route parameter\nfunction CourseDetail() {\n  const { id } = useParams();\n  const navigate = useNavigate();\n\n  return (\n    <div>\n      <h1>Course: {id}</h1>\n      <button onClick={() => navigate('/')}>Go Home</button>\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n\`\`\``, keyPoints: ['BrowserRouter wraps the entire app for routing.', 'NavLink adds active class for current route styling.', 'useParams() extracts dynamic URL segments.', 'useNavigate() for programmatic navigation.'] },

    { title: 'Build & Deploy', content: `\`npm run build\` compiles your React app into optimized static files (HTML, CSS, JS) in the \`dist/\` or \`build/\` folder. These files can be served by *any* static file server.\n\n### Build Optimization\n\nReact automatically **splits code into chunks**, minifies JavaScript, compresses CSS, and applies **tree-shaking** to remove unused code.\n\n### Deployment Options\n\n**Vercel** (zero-config, great for Next.js), **Netlify** (drag-and-drop deployment), **GitHub Pages** (free for static sites), **AWS S3 + CloudFront** (scalable CDN), and **Docker/Nginx** (self-hosted). For SPAs with client-side routing, configure the server to redirect all requests to \`index.html\`.\n\n\`\`\`bash\n# Build for production\nnpm run build\n\n# Preview the build locally\nnpm run preview\n\n# Deploy to Vercel\nnpx vercel --prod\n\n# Deploy to Netlify\nnpx netlify-cli deploy --prod --dir=dist\n\`\`\`\n\n\`\`\`nginx\n# Nginx config for SPA routing\nserver {\n  listen 80;\n  root /usr/share/nginx/html;\n  index index.html;\n\n  location / {\n    try_files $uri $uri/ /index.html;\n  }\n}\n\`\`\`\n\n\`\`\`dockerfile\n# Docker deployment via Multi-Stage build\nFROM node:20-alpine AS build\nWORKDIR /app\nCOPY package*.json .\nRUN npm ci\nCOPY . .\nRUN npm run build\n\nFROM nginx:alpine\nCOPY --from=build /app/dist /usr/share/nginx/html\n\`\`\``, keyPoints: ['npm run build creates optimized static files.', 'Vercel and Netlify offer zero-config deployment.', 'Configure server to redirect all routes to index.html.', 'Docker + Nginx for self-hosted production deployment.'] },

    { title: 'Best Practices & Code Standards', content: `Keep components **small and focused** — each component should have a single responsibility. If a component file exceeds 150-200 lines, it likely needs splitting. Extract reusable logic into **custom hooks** and presentational elements into smaller components.\n\n### Rules of Hooks\n\nHooks must be called at the **top level** of a component — never inside conditions, loops, or nested functions. This is not a style preference; it is required for React's internal tracking to work correctly. Use \`useMemo\` and \`useCallback\` only for **measurable** performance problems, not preventively.\n\n### Keys & State Management\n\nAlways use **stable, unique IDs** from your data as \`key\` props in lists — never use array indices (they break on reorder, filter, or insert). Lift state up to the nearest common parent when siblings need shared data. For global state, prefer **React Context** or lightweight libraries before reaching for Redux.\n\n\`\`\`jsx\n// DO: Hooks at the top level only\nfunction SearchResults({ query }) {\n  const [results, setResults] = useState([]);\n  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);\n  useEffect(() => { /* fetch */ }, [query]);\n  // ...\n}\n\n// DON'T: Hooks inside conditions -> THIS BREAKS REACT INTERNAL TRACKING!\nfunction InvalidSearchResults({ query }) {\n  if (query) {\n    const [results, setResults] = useState([]);\n  }\n}\n\`\`\`\n\n\`\`\`jsx\n// DO: Custom hooks for reusable logic\nfunction useDebounce(value, delay) {\n  const [debounced, setDebounced] = useState(value);\n  \n  useEffect(() => {\n    const timer = setTimeout(() => setDebounced(value), delay);\n    return () => clearTimeout(timer);\n  }, [value, delay]);\n  \n  return debounced;\n}\n\`\`\``, keyPoints: ['Keep components small and focused — one responsibility each.', 'Never use array index as key — use stable unique IDs from data.', 'Hooks must be called at the top level, never inside conditions.', 'Extract reusable logic into custom hooks.'] }
  ]
};
